{% extends 'extractors/_meta/extractor.j2' %}

{% block instructions %}
Identify each **distinct recipe** in the source — a dish title plus
an ingredient list plus a procedure. Skip "tip" boxes, glossaries,
ingredient lectures without steps, headnotes, and section
introductions.

Aim for completeness: every recipe in the source should appear once.

For each recipe:

- `name`: the dish title as the source presents it. Title Case if
  the source is loose; preserve culturally specific names verbatim
  (`Pasta alla Carbonara`, `Mapo Tofu`).
- `description`: 1–3 sentences. What the dish is, when to make it,
  what makes it distinctive. Pulled from the source's headnote if
  present.
- `yield` / `total_time`: optional metadata as the source states it
  (`"4 servings"`, `"45 min"`). Emit `null` when absent.
- `ingredients`: each entry a structured `{quantity, amount, unit,
  item, notes}` object — see the rules below.
- `steps`: ordered list. Imperative-mood, single sentence per step.
  Split source paragraphs that bundle multiple actions.
- `tags`: optional list of short tags (`"dessert"`, `"vegetarian"`,
  `"italian"`). Source-grounded; do not invent.
- `source_quote`: a verbatim passage from the source proving the
  recipe's presence — typically the dish's title line or first
  procedural sentence.

## Ingredient parsing rules

Each ingredient becomes a structured object. Curator's
build-replica step converts to metric deterministically using
`pint`, so your job is faithful structured parsing — DO NOT
compute metric values yourself.

For each ingredient line:

1. `quantity`: the verbatim quantity string from the source
   (e.g. `"2 1/4 cups"`, `"a pinch"`, `"1 stick"`).
2. `amount`: the numeric value as a JSON number. Mixed units
   flatten to a single canonical unit:
   `"1 lb 2 oz"` → `amount: 18, unit: "ounce"`.
   For descriptive (`a pinch`) or unitless (`1 egg`) quantities,
   set `amount: null`.
3. `unit`: the singular pint-known unit name. Use the canonical
   spelling: `cup`, `tablespoon`, `teaspoon`, `fluid_ounce`,
   `pint`, `quart`, `gallon`, `gram`, `kilogram`, `ounce`, `pound`,
   `inch`, `centimeter`, `stick`, `liter`, `milliliter`. For
   unitless counts (`1 egg`) and descriptive quantities, set
   `unit: null`.
4. `item`: the ingredient itself, lowercased unless it is a proper
   noun (`"all-purpose flour"`, `"Parmigiano-Reggiano"`).
5. `notes`: optional preparation note (`"softened"`, `"chopped"`,
   `"room temperature"`). Omit or set `null` when absent.

### Examples

| Source line                          | Parsed                                                                     |
| ------------------------------------ | -------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| `2 1/4 cups all-purpose flour`       | `{quantity: "2 1/4 cups", amount: 2.25, unit: "cup", item: "all-purpose flour"}` |
| `1 stick butter, softened`           | `{quantity: "1 stick", amount: 1, unit: "stick", item: "butter", notes: "softened"}` |
| `1 lb 2 oz bread flour`              | `{quantity: "1 lb 2 oz", amount: 18, unit: "ounce", item: "bread flour"}`  |
| `a pinch of salt`                    | `{quantity: "a pinch", amount: null, unit: null, item: "salt"}`            |
| `3 large eggs`                       | `{quantity: "3", amount: 3, unit: null, item: "eggs", notes: "large"}`     |
| `1 tsp vanilla extract`              | `{quantity: "1 tsp", amount: 1, unit: "teaspoon", item: "vanilla extract"}` |
| `300 g flour`                        | `{quantity: "300 g", amount: 300, unit: "gram", item: "flour"}`            |

## Step rewriting rules

Steps are freeform text; you (the LLM) handle their conversion
because parsing imperial measurements out of mid-sentence prose is
regex-fragile.

Rewrite each step inline:

- Fahrenheit → Celsius. `"Preheat oven to 375°F"` →
  `"Preheat oven to 190°C"`.
- Inches → cm. `"cut into 1-inch cubes"` → `"cut into 2.5 cm cubes"`.
- Cups / pounds / ounces / fl oz mid-sentence → ml/g equivalent.
- Leave `tsp`, `teaspoon`, `tbsp`, `tablespoon` alone (universal
  kitchen-spoon units).

Do NOT preserve the original alongside the metric in parentheses.
Steps read in metric.
{% endblock %}

{% block builder_calls %}

For each recipe (increment `<i>` per recipe — 0, 1, 2, ...):

    {{ vars.loom_sh }} output add {{ run.workdir }} --task {{ task.id }} \
        --set recipes.<i>.name='<dish name>' \
        --set recipes.<i>.description='<1-3 sentences>' \
        --set recipes.<i>.yield='<servings or null>' \
        --set recipes.<i>.total_time='<duration or null>' \
        --set recipes.<i>.source_quote='<verbatim passage>'

For each ingredient (`<j>` is the ingredient index within the recipe):

    {{ vars.loom_sh }} output add {{ run.workdir }} --task {{ task.id }} \
        --set recipes.<i>.ingredients.<j>.quantity='<verbatim or null>' \
        --set recipes.<i>.ingredients.<j>.amount=<number or null> \
        --set recipes.<i>.ingredients.<j>.unit='<pint unit or null>' \
        --set recipes.<i>.ingredients.<j>.item='<ingredient name>' \
        --set recipes.<i>.ingredients.<j>.notes='<prep note or null>'

For each step (`<k>` is the step index within the recipe):

    {{ vars.loom_sh }} output add {{ run.workdir }} --task {{ task.id }} \
        --set recipes.<i>.steps.<k>='<imperative-mood step text>'

For tags (when present):

    {{ vars.loom_sh }} output add {{ run.workdir }} --task {{ task.id }} \
        --set recipes.<i>.tags.0='<tag>' \
        --set recipes.<i>.tags.1='<tag>'
{% endblock %}
